Seagrasses are of utmost importance for marine ecological systems close to the shore line. Many studies deal with the function of seagrasses as primary producers, shelter and food for fish, turtles, and invertebrates as well as spawning areas for these organisms and as habitats for epiphytes (
Gillanders, 2006
; 
Gobert et al., 2006
; 
Ruiz et al., 2009
).

Existing reviews on seagrasses with a different focus than the present one deal in more detail with other aspects of the ecological role of these organisms and or particular compound classes, such as marine tannins (
Arnold and Targett, 2002
), plant–herbivore interactions (
Heck and Valentine, 2006
), functions of bioactive natural products from marine angiosperms (
Subhashini et al., 2013
), and plant-herbivore interactions, allelopathic properties, and anti-pathogen and anti-fouling activities of seagrasses (
Sieg and Kubanek, 2013
). Readers primarily interested in these aspects of seagrasses are therefore referred to these publications as the aspects covered in detail in those reviews, though partially linked to seagrass secondary metabolites, are here only briessy mentioned.

Primary metabolites were only cursory covered in this review (in this section) and macromolecular compounds such as cell wall polysaccharides (
Gloaguen et al., 2010
) and pectic galacturonans (
Popov et al., 2007
) were not covered. Seagrasses share their primary metabolism with higher plants inhabiting land and fresh water habitats, in particular with their closest relatives from the order 
Alismatales
s.l. (
Pirc, 1985
).

