Zostera tasmanica
(as
Heterozostera tasmanica
in the original paper) from Australia 10 . In a second broad based comparative study using paper chromatography and electrophoresis, McMillan et al. (1980) investigated the occurrence of sulfated phenolic acids and ssavonoids in 43 species from all currently accepted genera of seagrasses. All investigated species contained at least one class of sulfated compounds. Unfortunately, the authors just provided data of the number of different compounds found per compound class but made no attempts to identify the compounds. Interestingly, these authors missed the occurrence of sulfated phenolic acids in the genus
Zostera
though ten different taxa were analyzed. This is particularly interesting because zosteric acid 26 , a sulfated derivative of coumaric acid 25 , later found in
Z. marina (Todd et al., 1993)
and other species, is currently the most intensely studied natural product from seagrasses due to its antifouling bioactivity (see Sections 4.2 and 4.5).

