subSection.paragraph:
In his comprehensive review on marine natural product antifoulants, Clare (1996) mentioned zosteric acid 26 as the only antifouling compound from a higher plant. Ram et al. (2012) studied the antifoulant activity of zosteric acid 26 against quagga mussels (
Dreissena rostriformis subsp. bugensis
) and found a significant dose dependent effect. The need for a focused search for antifouling agents in marine organisms based on their ecological roles was also highlighted in the review of Fang et al. (2005) .

The chemical ecology of seagrasses is multifaceted (
Fig. 20
). Many aspects such as responses to ecological factors (Section 5.1), antifeedant activity of seagrass metabolites (Section 5.2), inssuence of primary and secondary metabolites on bird feeding preferences (Section 5.3), allelopathic effects of secondary metabolites from other organisms on seagrasses (Section 5.4), seagrasses and their secondary defence compounds as (indirect) promoters of biological invasions (Section 5.5), seasonal variation in secondary metabolites (Section 5.6), and seagrasses’ reactions to microbial infections have already been studied, while other aspects e.g. epibiont chemistry, inssuence of epibionts on competitiveness of seagrasses, potential protective functions of epibionts and their chemicals against predation (shared fate of host and symbiont/parasite), and uptake of natural and industrial chemicals from sediment (via the roots) and seawater (via the leaves) have not been studied yet. Moreover, some of the existing studies though addressing important ecological questions were performed using rather simple analytical techniques and only measured total amounts of compound classes and not quantities of individually characterized secondary metabolites.

As demonstrated above, though a lot of information on the chemistry of seagrasses is scattered through the literature, many gaps remain. The most apparent gaps concern the species of seagrasses which have not been investigated to date. However, due to the advent of new analytical techniques such as HPLC-MS comparative studies for the occurrence or absence of compounds already known from at least one species of seagrass should be relatively fast and easy to perform. Great care will have to be taken to correctly identify the analyzed species which are usually poor in diagnostic morphological characters. Moreover, future studies should ascertain that really genuine secondary metabolites from seagrasses and not artefacts from the extraction process or secondary metabolites from epibionts and/or from symbiontic, parasitic or pathogenic microorganisms will be studied (
Fig. 20
).
